### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

It's often tempting to make function calls in template bindings instead of using a pipe, due to the amount of boilerplate and setup that creating a pipe currently entails. This can result in performance bottlenecks, especially if the function is not cheap to compute and/or returns a value of a non-primitive data type.

I find this situation to usually occur, when there is derived state within items of an iterated collection. In the following example, consider `formatUserName` to be a function that is not cheap to compute and very specific to the component (i.e. low potential for app-wide reusability):
```html
<ul>
    @for (user of users; track user.jd) {
        <li>{{ formatUserName(user) }}</li>
    }
</ul>
```
The typical approaches in this situation would be:
- Writing a pure `| formatUserName` pipe. (-> boilerplate)
- Wrapping the list item in a component with `OnPush` change detection. (-> boilerplate, especially when the parent is not a standalone component).


### Proposed solution

Introducing a decorator for creating pipes from component-local functions, e.g.:
```js
@Component({
    template: `<ul>
        @for (user of users; track user.jd) {
            <li>{{ user | formatUserName }}</li>
        }
    </ul>`,
    // ...
})
class ContactListComponent {
    // ...

    @LocalPipe() // `name` defaults to the name of the function, `pure` defaults to `true`
    formatUserName(user: User): string {
        // some computation ...
    }
}
```

### Alternatives considered

In our project, we added generic `@Cached()` and `@AsyncCached` (adding `shareReplay` to the returned observable) function annotations that fulfill a similar purpose, but don't offer the same degree of optimization and syntactic sugar.

